  "prompt": "Is internal hard drive a primary storage device or secondary storage device?",
  "response": "An **internal hard drive** is generally considered a **secondary storage device**.\n\n### Explanation:\n- **Primary Storage**: This refers to memory that is directly accessible by the CPU, such as **RAM (Random Access Memory)** and **cache memory**. Primary storage is volatile, meaning it only retains data while the computer is powered on.\n- **Secondary Storage**: This refers to non-volatile storage devices that retain data even when the power is turned off. Examples include **hard drives (HDDs)**, **solid-state drives (SSDs)**, **external drives**, and **optical media (CDs/DVDs)**. Internal hard drives fall into this category because they store data permanently and are not directly accessed by the CPU but rather through the computer's I/O subsystem.\n\nWhile the internal hard drive houses the operating system, applications, and user data, it is not directly accessed by the CPU in the same way as primary storage. Instead, data is first loaded from the hard drive into RAM (primary storage) for processing by the CPU.\n\nSo, in summary, an internal hard drive is a **secondary storage device**.",
